tolerating Georgiana's

800
00:44:15,010 --> 00:44:16,750
Laxity in other things.

801
00:44:16,750 --> 00:44:19,270
She does know how
to make good coffee.

802
00:44:19,270 --> 00:44:21,080
Thank you.

803
00:44:21,080 --> 00:44:24,090
She brings it to me every
night at exactly 10 o'clock.

804
00:44:24,090 --> 00:44:27,590
And when I've drunk it all,
then I know it's time to quit.

805
00:44:27,590 --> 00:44:30,520
Yes, and eat breakfast so
you can have more coffee.

806
00:44:30,520 --> 00:44:31,980
Oh.

807
00:44:31,980 --> 00:44:33,450
[CHUCKLES]

808
00:44:41,260 --> 00:44:44,380
Georgiana, you
mustn't lie like that!

809
00:44:47,370 --> 00:44:50,850
You'll get yourself [INAUDIBLE].

810
00:44:50,850 --> 00:44:53,490
G... Georgiana?

811
00:44:53,490 --> 00:44:56,970
[SCREAMS]

812
00:44:56,970 --> 00:44:58,460
That was Auntie!

813
00:45:08,200 --> 00:45:08,900
Auntie!

814
00:45:13,370 --> 00:45:14,370
Oh!

815
00:45:14,370 --> 00:45:15,360
I'm all right.

816
00:45:15,360 --> 00:45:17,850
I'm all right now.

817
00:45:17,850 --> 00:45:19,500
Emil, help Frau
Schnappman [INAUDIBLE].

818
00:45:19,500 --> 00:45:20,330
AUNT GUSSIE: [INAUDIBLE].

819
00:45:24,600 --> 00:45:25,300
[SCREAMS]

820
00:45:25,300 --> 00:45:26,000
It's OK.

821
00:45:26,000 --> 00:45:27,290
Don't be afraid.

822
00:45:36,270 --> 00:45:39,530
The same two wounds, Doctor.

823
00:45:39,530 --> 00:45:42,850
And my last words to her
were angry ones, a petulant

824
00:45:42,850 --> 00:45:45,430
Reprimand for being
late with my coffee.

825
00:45:45,430 --> 00:45:46,290
What time was that?

826
00:45:46,290 --> 00:45:48,790
About two or three
minutes after 10:00.

827
00:45:48,790 --> 00:45:50,470
She's been then
about 45 minutes.

828
00:45:54,620 --> 00:45:55,880
Bloodless, like the rest.

829
00:45:59,590 --> 00:46:00,500
Passes all belief!

830
00:46:03,770 --> 00:46:07,520
Ruth's aunt saw Herman Gleib
in the garden this morning.

831
00:46:07,520 --> 00:46:08,970
Could it be that he...?

832
00:46:19,430 --> 00:46:21,510
You were the first one here.

833
00:46:21,510 --> 00:46:22,900
What happened?

834
00:46:22,900 --> 00:46:24,840
I was in my room reading.

835
00:46:24,840 --> 00:46:26,760
My door was open.

836
00:46:26,760 --> 00:46:28,360
I must have dozed off
for a minute or so,

837
00:46:28,360 --> 00:46:30,840
Because I awoke to hear
Frau Schnappman scream.

838
00:46:30,840 --> 00:46:32,390
You say your door was open?

839
00:46:32,390 --> 00:46:34,560
Yes, my room was very
poorly ventilated.

840
00:46:34,560 --> 00:46:35,900
And you saw nothing?

841
00:46:35,900 --> 00:46:37,860
Heard nothing unusual?

842
00:46:37,860 --> 00:46:38,550
EMIL: Nothing.

843
00:46:41,430 --> 00:46:42,560
Karl.

844
00:46:42,560 --> 00:46:44,390
What is it?

845
00:46:44,390 --> 00:46:47,740
This crucifix
belonged to Martha.

846
00:46:47,740 --> 00:46:49,660
[BELL RINGING]

847
00:46:49,660 --> 00:46:50,360
See who it is, Emil.

848
00:46:53,540 --> 00:46:55,970
Can you positively identify
this as belonging to Martha?

849
00:46:55,970 --> 00:46:57,520
Without a doubt.

850
00:46:57,520 --> 00:47:00,590
I saw it in her room
the night she died.

851
00:47:00,590 --> 00:47:02,280
How in the world
did it get here?

852
00:47:02,280 --> 00:47:04,170
Herman Gleib was in her room.

853
00:47:04,170 --> 00:47:06,060
He had that crucifix
in his hands.

854
00:47:06,060 --> 00:47:08,830
And Herman was here today.

855
00:47:11,660 --> 00:47:13,500
Maybe here now,
for all we know.

856
00:47:19,980 --> 00:47:24,430
[KNOCK ON DOOR]

857
00:47:24,430 --> 00:47:25,640
Who is it?

858
00:47:25,640 --> 00:47:26,330
KARL: Karl:

859
00:47:26,330 --> 00:47:27,030
Oh.

860
00:47:30,620 --> 00:47:31,540
How is she?

861
00:47:31,540 --> 00:47:33,510
She's had a real shock this
time, but she'll be all right.

862
00:47:33,510 --> 00:47:34,910
I'm putting her to bed.

863
00:47:34,910 --> 00:47:36,030
Leave her there.

864
00:47:36,030 --> 00:47:37,210
Don't let her out of this room.

865
00:47:37,210 --> 00:47:38,510
And don't you leave it, either.

866
00:47:38,510 --> 00:47:39,970
Well, what do you mean?

867
00:47:39,970 --> 00:47:42,800
It looks as if Herman Gleib
is the killer after all.

868
00:47:42,800 --> 00:47:45,610
It's possible he may be
hiding here in the castle.

869
00:47:45,610 --> 00:47:46,520
What makes you think so?

870
00:47:46,520 --> 00:47:47,880
I'll tell you later.

871
00:47:47,880 --> 00:47:50,860
Stay in your room and
keep your door locked.

872
00:47:50,860 --> 00:47:52,330
Don't worry about that.

873
00:47:57,230 --> 00:47:59,190
I heard every word he said.

874
00:47:59,190 --> 00:48:00,500
And I don't think
there's any use

875
00:48:00,500 --> 00:48:02,130
Of them searching for Herman.

876
00:48:02,130 --> 00:48:05,070
They should look for a
dog, a human-faced dog.

877
00:48:05,070 --> 00:48:07,030
Auntie, the doors and
windows are all locked.

878
00:48:07,030 --> 00:48:08,460
There's nothing to
be afraid of now.

879
00:48:08,460 --> 00:48:09,790
Well, who said I was afraid?

880
00:48:09,790 --> 00:48:10,490
I'm not a bit afraid.

881
00:48:10,490 --> 00:48:12,070
No, of course
you're not afraid,

882
00:48:12,070 --> 00:48:13,440
But you must get some rest.

883
00:48:13,440 --> 00:48:15,270
Rest in this awful place?

884
00:48:15,270 --> 00:48:18,980
With dog-faced Hermans
and human-faced bats

885
00:48:18,980 --> 00:48:21,470
And bloods and
murders and vampires!

886
00:48:31,440 --> 00:48:33,820
Find anything, Karl?

887
00:48:33,820 --> 00:48:36,600
There's an unbroken
cup over in that window.

888
00:48:36,600 --> 00:48:38,190
If Herman did it, he
came through the door.

889
00:48:38,190 --> 00:48:39,980
He must've.

890
00:48:39,980 --> 00:48:41,840
And yet I don't understand
how he could find

891
00:48:41,840 --> 00:48:44,120
His way up here
without us hearing him.

892
00:48:44,120 --> 00:48:48,360
Yet Emil was asleep, and
I was in the library.

893
00:48:48,360 --> 00:48:50,330
Yes, he could have done it.

894
00:48:50,330 --> 00:48:53,280
The facts all point to it.

895
00:48:53,280 --> 00:48:54,360
What was it, Emil?

896
00:48:54,360 --> 00:48:55,370
The Burgermeister.

897
00:48:55,370 --> 00:49:00,160
He has new for Herr
Brettschneider about Herman.

898
00:49:00,160 --> 00:49:00,860
Huh.

899
00:49:11,340 --> 00:49:13,890
Pardon the intrusion,
Doctor, pardon the intrusion.

900
00:49:13,890 --> 00:49:16,280
I knew Karl was here and
I though you wouldn't mind

901
00:49:16,280 --> 00:49:18,350
If I ran in to
tell him the news.

902
00:49:18,350 --> 00:49:19,100
About Herman?

903
00:49:19,100 --> 00:49:20,320
Yes.

904
00:49:20,320 --> 00:49:23,090
He fell into the Devil's
Well in the cave.

905
00:49:23,090 --> 00:49:24,580
KARL: He's dead?

906
00:49:24,580 --> 00:49:26,320
BURGERMEISTER:
Dead as a doornail.

907
00:49:26,320 --> 00:49:28,500
This ends our troubles, Karl!

908
00:49:28,500 --> 00:49:29,860
The vampire's dead!

909
00:49:29,860 --> 00:49:31,790
I can feel it in my bones!

910
00:49:31,790 --> 00:49:33,050
Hmm.

911
00:49:33,050 --> 00:49:35,490
Well your bones may be wrong.

912
00:49:35,490 --> 00:49:37,140
What time did this happen?

913
00:49:37,140 --> 00:49:39,160
BURGERMEISTER: Quite
early, about 9 o'clock.

914
00:49:39,160 --> 00:49:40,900
The cave is nearly
two hours from here.

915
00:49:40,900 --> 00:49:43,650
That's why we didn't
hear it sooner.

916
00:49:43,650 --> 00:49:45,180
Well, it may interest
you to know that there's

917
00:49:45,180 --> 00:49:49,600
Been another death,
after your vampire died.

918
00:49:49,600 --> 00:49:50,440
Who?

919
00:49:50,440 --> 00:49:51,140
Who?

920
00:49:51,140 --> 00:49:53,610
Dr. Niemann's housekeeper,
right here in her own room.

921
00:49:53,610 --> 00:49:55,360
Mother of mercy!

922
00:49:55,360 --> 00:49:56,730
What are we going to do?

923
00:49:56,730 --> 00:49:59,490
But a natural death wouldn't
kill a vampire, Karl.

924
00:49:59,490 --> 00:50:03,060
You know the expected theory, a
stake driven through the heart.

925
00:50:03,060 --> 00:50:04,680
Oh yes, that's the
theory all right.

926
00:50:04,680 --> 00:50:05,890
But... but... but...

927
00:50:05,890 --> 00:50:06,600
But what?

928
00:50:06,600 --> 00:50:08,460
But they did!

929
00:50:08,460 --> 00:50:10,620
They drove a stake
through his heart!

930
00:50:10,620 --> 00:50:12,530
Good God, are we living
in the Middle Ages?

931
00:50:12,530 --> 00:50:15,110
It wasn't through
my sanction, Karl.

932
00:50:15,110 --> 00:50:16,250
Sauer did it.

933
00:50:16,250 --> 00:50:17,310
He told me so himself.

934
00:50:19,960 --> 00:50:23,220
Well, that ends the vampire
theory as far as I'm concerned.

935
00:50:23,220 --> 00:50:25,220
Herman Gleib died in
the accepted fashion

936
00:50:25,220 --> 00:50:27,470
For killing a vampire.

937
00:50:27,470 --> 00:50:31,170
Oh no, there's some human agency
at work here, Doctor, a madman

938
00:50:31,170 --> 00:50:34,360
Who kills to satisfy some
violent, sadistic urge!

939
00:50:34,360 --> 00:50:35,870
Yes, you're right, Karl.

940
00:50:35,870 --> 00:50:40,700
I've been a fool, a
superstitious fool!

941
00:50:40,700 --> 00:50:42,240
Did they leave his
body in the cave?

942
00:50:42,240 --> 00:50:43,360
Yes.

943
00:50:43,360 --> 00:50:45,380
Yes, they did.

944
00:50:45,380 --> 00:50:46,510
Well, in view of
what's happened,

945
00:50:46,510 --> 00:50:48,660
Don't you think you owe
him a decent burial?

946
00:50:48,660 --> 00:50:49,830
You're right.

947
00:50:49,830 --> 00:50:53,710
In view of what has happened,
we do owe him that, Karl.

948
00:50:53,710 --> 00:50:55,510
I'll see to it at once,
this very instant.

949
00:50:55,510 --> 00:50:58,320
And I'll make arrangements
for Georgiana's removal

950
00:50:58,320 --> 00:50:59,460
To the morgue.

951
00:50:59,460 --> 00:51:00,640
Goodnight, Doctor.

952
00:51:00,640 --> 00:51:01,830
Pardon the intrusion.

953
00:51:01,830 --> 00:51:02,530
Goodnight, Gustav.

954
00:51:02,530 --> 00:51:03,730
BURGERMEISTER:
Pardon the intrusion.

955
00:51:03,730 --> 00:51:06,360
[DOOR CLOSES]

956
00:51:06,360 --> 00:51:08,700
Well.

957
00:51:08,700 --> 00:51:11,850
Here I am, just where
I started weeks ago.

958
00:51:11,850 --> 00:51:14,030
There isn't a single
theory that doesn't

959
00:51:14,030 --> 00:51:17,250
Lead straight into a stone wall.

960
00:51:17,250 --> 00:51:19,000
I've jested about
this vampire business

961
00:51:19,000 --> 00:51:22,220
Because my better judgment told
me it was a lot of nonsense.

962
00:51:22,220 --> 00:51:24,140
Then I reached the point
where I was willing to accept

963
00:51:24,140 --> 00:51:28,360
Even that, Because it seemed
to satisfy the equation.

964
00:51:28,360 --> 00:51:31,540
All of it a bit superstitious.

965
00:51:31,540 --> 00:51:34,030
I don't know which way
to turn, where to look,

966
00:51:34,030 --> 00:51:36,210
What to look for!

967
00:51:36,210 --> 00:51:39,010
Why should anyone
want human blood?

968
00:51:39,010 --> 00:51:39,710
Why?

969
00:51:39,710 --> 00:51:40,410
Why?!

970
00:51:40,410 --> 00:51:42,020
Calm yourself, Karl.

971
00:51:42,020 --> 00:51:43,460
Calm myself?

972
00:51:43,460 --> 00:51:44,420
Calm myself?

973
00:51:44,420 --> 00:51:46,190
With all these unsolved
murders staring me

974
00:51:46,190 --> 00:51:48,640
In the face and no
solution in sight?

975
00:51:53,340 --> 00:51:56,130
How much blood is there
in a human body, Doctor?

976
00:51:56,130 --> 00:51:59,640
About six liters,
approximately.

977
00:51:59,640 --> 00:52:01,760
Can you think of any purpose
for which that amount of blood

978
00:52:01,760 --> 00:52:04,580
Might be used?

979
00:52:04,580 --> 00:52:07,370
No, not even in transfusions.

980
00:52:07,370 --> 00:52:09,720
KARL: That's the
point which stops me.

981
00:52:09,720 --> 00:52:12,770
There isn't any other
use for human blood.

982
00:52:12,770 --> 00:52:14,460
Gah!

983
00:52:14,460 --> 00:52:16,540
Murderers leave clues!

984
00:52:16,540 --> 00:52:18,890
And these atrocities
are murders, Doctor.

985
00:52:18,890 --> 00:52:20,260
Those simple fools
in the village

986
00:52:20,260 --> 00:52:21,160
Can believe what they like.

987
00:52:21,160 --> 00:52:23,050
But you and I are
sane, thinking people.

988
00:52:23,050 --> 00:52:27,530
And you know and I know,
Doctor, that these are murders!

989
00:52:27,530 --> 00:52:30,670
The last one was done
here, in this very house,

990
00:52:30,670 --> 00:52:33,060
Right under this roof.

991
00:52:33,060 --> 00:52:35,530
All right, I'll start here.

992
00:52:35,530 --> 00:52:37,390
I'm going over every
foot of this place,

993
00:52:37,390 --> 00:52:39,070
Both inside and out.

994
00:52:39,070 --> 00:52:40,710
Nobody, sane or insane,
is clever enough

995
00:52:40,710 --> 00:52:43,350
To get away with murder without
leaving a clue of some sort!

996
00:52:43,350 --> 00:52:45,140
And I'm going to find that clue!

997
00:52:45,140 --> 00:52:47,490
Come, come Karl, you musn't let
your nerves run away with you.

998
00:52:47,490 --> 00:52:49,150
Here, these.

999
00:52:53,930 --> 00:52:55,590
These will help to give
you a good night's sleep.

1000
00:52:58,860 --> 00:53:01,770
If there are any clues,
they'll be here in the morning

1001
00:53:01,770 --> 00:53:06,630
When your nerves are calm and
your... your mind is clear.

1002
00:53:06,630 --> 00:53:08,950
Take my advice and
go home and rest.

1003
00:53:08,950 --> 00:53:10,080
I imagined a
thousand demons were

1004
00:53:10,080 --> 00:53:12,090
After me as I came
down those stairs!

1005
00:53:12,090 --> 00:53:14,320
Ruth, didn't I tell you
to stay in your room?

1006
00:53:14,320 --> 00:53:16,730
Yes, but I wanted the doctor
to come up and quiet Auntie.

1007
00:53:16,730 --> 00:53:18,540
You know, it isn't her
imagination this time.

1008
00:53:18,540 --> 00:53:19,440
Of course, Ruth.

1009
00:53:19,440 --> 00:53:20,350
I'll come right away.

1010
00:53:20,350 --> 00:53:22,080
Take my advice, young man.

1011
00:53:22,080 --> 00:53:24,580
Go home and go to bed.

1012
00:53:24,580 --> 00:53:27,070
Goodnight, Karl.

1013
00:53:27,070 --> 00:53:28,070
Goodnight, Ruth.

1014
00:53:35,040 --> 00:53:36,540
DR. VON NIEMANN:
Goodnight, Karl.

1015
00:53:36,540 --> 00:53:37,530
Goodnight, Doctor.

1016
00:54:04,420 --> 00:54:05,920
[CLOCK CHIMING]

1017
00:54:53,370 --> 00:54:59,860
If his lights are on,
you must wait, Emil.

1018
00:54:59,860 --> 00:55:01,570
Wait until he has gone to bed.

1019
00:56:43,100 --> 00:56:44,950
Handle him as you
did the others, Emil.

1020
00:56:47,900 --> 00:56:51,540
You are strong, very strong.

1021
00:56:56,120 --> 00:57:00,280
I am waiting for
you, waiting for you

1022
00:57:00,280 --> 00:57:01,320
To bring him to the laboratory.

1023
00:57:29,630 --> 00:57:31,120
[KNOCKING ON DOOR]

1024
00:57:40,090 --> 00:57:41,580
You!

1025
00:57:41,580 --> 00:57:43,070
You're the one!

1026
00:57:43,070 --> 00:57:44,570
What mad thing are you doing?

1027
00:57:44,570 --> 00:57:45,560
Mad?

1028
00:57:45,560 --> 00:57:48,720
Is one who has sold the secret
of life to be considered mad?

1029
00:57:48,720 --> 00:57:50,090
Life!

1030
00:57:50,090 --> 00:57:51,770
Created in the laboratory!

1031
00:57:51,770 --> 00:57:56,440
No mere crystalline growth, but
tissue, living, growing tissue,

1032
00:57:56,440 --> 00:57:59,030
Life that moves,
pulsates, and demands

1033
00:57:59,030 --> 00:58:01,610
Food for its continued growth!

1034
00:58:01,610 --> 00:58:04,750
Ha, you shudder in horror.

1035
00:58:04,750 --> 00:58:06,770
So did I the first time.

1036
00:58:06,770 --> 00:58:08,670
But what are a few lives
being weighed in the balance

1037
00:58:08,670 --> 00:58:11,080
Against the achievement
of biological science?

1038
00:58:11,080 --> 00:58:12,950
Think of it.

1039
00:58:12,950 --> 00:58:14,810
I have lifted the babe.

1040
00:58:14,810 --> 00:58:18,550
I have created life, wrested
the secret of life from life!

1041
00:58:18,550 --> 00:58:20,240
Now do you understand?

1042
00:58:20,240 --> 00:58:22,760
From the lives of those
who have gone before,

1043
00:58:22,760 --> 00:58:24,760
I have created life!

1044
00:58:24,760 --> 00:58:27,720
I'll tell Karl!

1045
00:58:27,720 --> 00:58:33,560
You may, for tonight Karl's
name will be added to yours,

1046
00:58:33,560 --> 00:58:37,540
And all of those who
misachieved within mortal lives.

1047
00:58:42,510 --> 00:58:44,500
[MACHINE WHIRRING]

1048
01:00:06,140 --> 01:00:08,260
I didn't take your
sleeping tablets, Doctor.

1049
01:00:44,380 --> 01:00:47,210
Emil brought them here.

1050
01:00:47,210 --> 01:00:48,260
He's the one who murdered them!

1051
01:00:48,260 --> 01:00:49,170
Stay where you are.

1052
01:00:49,170 --> 01:00:50,770
You'll have a chance to
tell everything, Doctor.

1053
01:00:54,510 --> 01:00:56,490
[THUMPING AND STOMPING NOISES]

1054
01:01:02,430 --> 01:01:04,410
I'll take care of von Niemann!

1055
01:01:04,410 --> 01:01:05,890
Get her out of here!

1056
01:01:25,690 --> 01:01:27,670
[GUNSHOT]

1057
01:01:27,670 --> 01:01:28,660
[CRASH]

1058
01:01:28,660 --> 01:01:30,150
You stay here.

1059
